e supersonic downflows, by far the most common one appears to be\nthe draining of plasma along the legs of rising magnetic loops. The loops\nmainly drain into forming pores. The line-of-sight velocities of the supersonic\ndownflows reach up to 49 kms-1 and the velocity distribution shows multiple\npopulations. Almost 92% of these supersonic downflows coexist with a subsonic\nflow component. The weaker, more horizontal fields associated with the\nsupersonic component suggests that it is formed above the subsonic component.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Feb 2022 18:38:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 25 Jul 2022 08:23:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-26"}
